f="/wiki/Fighting_Discrimination" title="Fighting Discrimination">Fighting Discrimination</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Human_rights" title="Human rights">Human rights</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Intersex_human_rights" title="Intersex human rights">Intersex rights</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Masculism" title="Masculism">Masculism</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Multiculturalism" title="Multiculturalism">Multiculturalism</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Racial_integration" title="Racial integration">Racial integration</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Self-determination" title="Self-determination">Self-determination</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Social_integration" title="Social integration">Social integration</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Toleration" title="Toleration">Toleration</a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style="padding:0 0.1em 0.4em;padding-left:0; padding-right:0;">\n<div class="NavFrame collapsed" style="border:none;padding:0">\n<div class="NavHead" style="font-size:105%;background:transparent;text-align:left;background:thistle;padding-bottom:0;text-align:center;">Related topics</div>\n<div class="NavContent hlist" style="font-size:105%;padding:0.2em 0 0.4em;text-align:center;padding-top:0;">\n<ul>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Allophilia" title="Allophilia">Allophilia</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/List_of_anti-cultural,_anti-national,_and_anti-ethnic_terms" title="List of anti-cultural, anti-national, and anti-ethnic terms">Anti-cultural sentiment</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Cultural_assimilation" title="Cultural assimilation">Assimilation</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Bias" title="Bias">Bias</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Christian_privilege" title="Christian privilege">Christian privilege</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Diversity_(politics)" title="Diversity (politics)">Diversity</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Ethnic_penalty" title="Ethnic penalty">Ethnic penalty</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Eugenics" title="Eugenics">Eugenics</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Intersectionality" title="Intersectionality">Intersectionality</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Male_privilege" title="Male privilege">Male privilege</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Multiculturalism" title="Multiculturalism">Multiculturalism</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Neurodiversity" title="Neurodiversity">Neurodiversity</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Oppression" title="Oppression">Oppression</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Police_brutality" title="Police brutality">Police brutality</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Political_correctness" title="Political correctness">Political correctness</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Power_distance" title="Power distance">Power distance</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Prejudice" title="Prejudice">Prejudice</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Racial_bias_in_criminal_news_in_the_United_States" title="Racial bias in criminal news in the United States">Racial bias in criminal news</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Racism_by_country" title="Racism by country">Racism by country</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Regressive_left" title="Regressive left">Regressive left</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Religious_intolerance" title="Religious intolerance">Religious intolerance</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Second-generation_gender_bias" title="Second-generation gender bias">Second-generation gender bias</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Snob" title="Snob">Snobbery</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Social_exclusion" title="Social exclusion">Social exclusion</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Social_stigma" title="Social stigma">Social stigma</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Stereotype" title="Stereotype">Stereotype</a>\n<ul>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Stereotype_threat" title="Stereotype threat">threat</a></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/White_privilege" title="White privilege">White privilege</a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style="padding:0.3em 0.4em 0.3em;font-weight:bold;border-top: 1px solid #aaa; border-bottom: 1px solid #aaa;padding-top:0.1em;font-style:italic;"><a href="/wiki/File:Disclogo1.svg" class="image"><img alt="Disclogo1.svg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/ff/Disclogo1.svg/10px-Disclogo1.svg.png" width="10" height="16" class="noviewer" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/ff/Disclogo1.svg/16px-Disclogo1.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/ff/Disclogo1.svg/21px-Disclogo1.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="169" data-file-height="254" /></a> <a href="/wiki/Portal:Discrimination" title="Portal:Discrimination">Discrimination portal</a></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style="text-align:right;font-size:115%;padding-top: 0.6em;">\n<div class="plainlinks hlist navbar mini">\n<ul>\n<li class="nv-view"><a href="/wiki/Template:Discrimination_sidebar" title="Template:Discrimination sidebar"><abbr title="View this template">v</abbr></a></li>\n<li class="nv-talk"><a href="/wiki/Template_talk:Discrimination_sidebar" title="Template talk:Discrimination sidebar"><abbr title="Discuss this template">t</abbr></a></li>\n<li class="nv-edit"><a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Template:Discrimination_sidebar&amp;action=edit"><abbr title="Edit this template">e</abbr></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</table>\n<p>Different theories have been provided to explain these racial discrepancies. Jay Cassano, writing for <i><a href="/wiki/Fast_Company_(magazine)" title="Fast Company (magazine)">Fast Company</a></i> magazine, argued that Wikipedia\'s small proportion of black editors is a result of the small black presence within the technology sector, and a relative lack of reliable access to the Internet.<sup id="cite_ref-Fast_Company_4-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Fast_Company-4">[4]</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Katherine_Maher" title="Katherine Maher">Katherine Maher</a>, executive director of the <a href="/wiki/Wikimedia_Foundation" title="Wikimedia Foundation">Wikimedia Foundation</a>, has argued that focuses in Wikipedia\'s content are representative of those of society as a whole. She said that Wikipedia could only represent that which was referenced in <a href="/wiki/Secondary_sources" class="mw-redirect" title="Secondary sources">secondary sources</a>, which historically have been favourable towards and focused on white men.<sup id="cite_ref-Wired_5-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Wired-5">[5]</a></sup> \xe2\x80\x9cStudies have shown that content on Wikipedia suffers from the bias of its editors \xe2\x80\x93 [who are] mainly <a href="/wiki/High_technology" class="mw-redirect" title="High technology">technically inclined</a>, English-speaking, <a href="/wiki/White-collar_worker" title="White-collar worker">white-collar</a> men living in majority-Christian, developed countries in the Northern hemisphere\xe2\x80\x9d.<sup id="cite_ref-huffpo-15apr2015_6-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-huffpo-15apr2015-6">[6]</a></sup></p>\n<p></p>\n<div id="toc" class="toc">\n<div class="toctitle">\n<h2>Contents</h2>\n</div>\n<ul>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-1"><a href="#Analysis"><span class="tocnumber">1</span> <span class="toctext">Analysis</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-2"><a href="#Responses"><span class="tocnumber">2</span> <span class="toctext">Responses</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-3"><a href="#See_also"><span class="tocnumber">3</span> <span class="toctext">See also</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-4"><a href="#References"><span class="tocnumber">4</span> <span class="toctext">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<p></p>\n<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Analysis">Analysis</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Racial_bias_on_Wikipedia&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: Analysis">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>According to Maira Liriano, the associate chief librarian at New York City\xe2\x80\x99s Schomburg Center, one of the biggest challenges is getting new editors to keep editing Wikipedia after the edit-a-thon is over.<sup id="cite_ref-huffpo-15apr2015_6-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-huffpo-15apr2015-6">[6]</a></sup> One challenge with retaining new editors is that the \xe2\x80\x9c[n]erdy white guys\xe2\x80\x9d who predominate as Wikipedia editors \xe2\x80\x9c\xe2\x80\xa6aren\'t always warm and nurturing\xe2\x80\x9d to new editors.<sup id="cite_ref-huffpo-15apr2015_6-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-huffpo-15apr2015-6">[6]</a></sup> For example, when new editors add content on Black history, their content may be deleted by established editors. As well, when new editors are trying to advocate for the inclusion of Black history content on Wikipedia\xe2\x80\x99s talk pages (each article has an associated talk page for discussion of changes), the \xe2\x80\x9c[c]omments [to new editors] on [Wikipedia article] talk pages can be very blunt.\xe2\x80\x9d<sup id="cite_ref-huffpo-15apr2015_6-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-huffpo-15apr2015-6">[6]</a></sup> An issue for women of colour is that \xe2\x80\x9cwomen in many communities have less leisure time than men,\xe2\x80\x9d according to Siko Bouterse, the director of community resources at the Wikimedia Foundation.<sup id="cite_ref-huffpo-15apr2015_6-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-huffpo-15apr2015-6">[6]</a></sup></p>\n<p>Another challenge for editors trying to add Black history articles to Wikipedia is the requirement that potential article topics, such as historical individuals or events, meet Wikipedia\xe2\x80\x99s \xe2\x80\x9c<a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Notability" title="Wikipedia:Notability">notability</a>\xe2\x80\x9d criteria.<sup id="cite_ref-huffpo-15apr2015_6-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-huffpo-15apr2015-6">[6]</a></sup> \xe2\x80\x98\xe2\x80\x99HuffPost\xe2\x80\x99\xe2\x80\x99 states that the Wikipedia notability criteria \xe2\x80\x9c\xe2\x80\xa6is a troubling problem for those fighting for more content about women and minorities\xe2\x80\x9d, because \xe2\x80\x9c\xe2\x80\xa6there\'s simply less [published] documentation on many accomplished women and minorities throughout history -- they were often ignored, after all, or forced to make their contributions as someone else\'s assistant\xe2\x80\x9d.<sup id="cite_ref-huffpo-15apr2015_6-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-huffpo-15apr2015-6">[6]</a></sup></p>\n<p>Maher states that one issue is that \xe2\x80\x9c\xe2\x80\xa6content on Wikipedia has to be backed up by <a href="/wiki/Secondary_source" title="Secondary source">secondary sources</a>, sources that she says throughout history have contained a bias toward white men\xe2\x80\x9d; \xe2\x80\x9c\xe2\x80\xa6people of color have not been represented in mainstream knowledge creation or inclusion in that knowledge,\xe2\x80\x9d as \xe2\x80\x9c\xe2\x80\xa6encyclopedias of old were mostly written by European men.\xe2\x80\x9d<sup id="cite_ref-Wired_5-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Wired-5">[5]</a></sup> Another issue is the \xe2\x80\x9coften abusive relationships between editors\xe2\x80\x9d on talk pages, which \xe2\x80\x9c\xe2\x80\xa6can make Wikipedia a less than welcoming place for \xe2\x80\xa6minority groups looking to get involved\xe2\x80\x9d in editing Wikipedia.<sup id="cite_ref-Wired_5-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Wired-5">[5]</a></sup> The Wikipedia editing "...community can also appear hostile, both to outsiders looking in and to those involved in it" by editing articles; indeed, article "[t]alk pages [discussions about articles] routinely devolve into seemingly petty arguments".<sup id="cite_ref-atlantic-18nov2015_7-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-atlantic-18nov2015-7">[7]</a></sup></p>\n<p>There has been "...criticism of bias [on Wikipedia], both on individual pages [articles] and as a systemic mind-set that the editing network has as a whole."<sup id="cite_ref-atlantic-18nov2015_7-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-atlantic-18nov2015-7">[7]</a></sup> <a href="/w/index.php?title=William_Beutler&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="William Beutler (page does not exist)">William Beutler</a>, author of the blog <a href="/w/index.php?title=The_Wikipedian&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="The Wikipedian (page does not exist)">The Wikipedian</a> and a consultant on Wikipedia issues for clients, states that "...certain areas of Wikipedia, including certain political areas of Wikipedia...tend to be controlled by a small number of editors who tend to see things the same way."<sup id="cite_ref-atlantic-18nov2015_7-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-atlantic-18nov2015-7">[7]</a></sup> Various communities have raised concerns about "...Wikipedia and its editors, saying that the pages had obvious systemic bias against them."<sup id="cite_ref-atlantic-18nov2015_7-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-atlantic-18nov2015-7">[7]</a></sup></p>\n<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Responses">Responses</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Racial_bias_on_Wikipedia&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Responses">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class="thumb tright">\n<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:WikiConference_North_America_20170810-7225.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0b/WikiConference_North_America_20170810-7225.jpg/220px-WikiConference_North_America_20170810-7225.jpg" width="220" height="150" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0b/WikiConference_North_America_20170810-7225.jpg/330px-WikiConference_North_America_20170810-7225.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0b/WikiConference_North_America_20170810-7225.jpg/440px-WikiConference_North_America_20170810-7225.jpg 2x" data-file-width="5098" data-file-height="3474" /></a>\n<div class="thumbcaption">\n<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:WikiConference_North_America_20170810-7225.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>\nSherry Antoine of <a href="/wiki/AfroCrowd" title="AfroCrowd">AfroCROWD</a> presents at <a href="/wiki/WikiConference_North_America" title="WikiConference North America">WikiConference North America</a>, August 2017</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<p>Attempts have been made to rectify racial biases through <a href="/wiki/Edit-a-thon" title="Edit-a-thon">edit-a-thons</a>, organised events at which Wikipedia editors attempt to improve coverage of certain topics and train new editors. In February 2015, multiple edit-a-thons were organised to commemorate <a href="/wiki/Black_History_Month" title="Black History Month">Black History Month</a> in the <a href="/wiki/United_States_of_America" class="mw-redirect" title="United States of America">United States of America</a>. One such edit-a-thon was organized by the <a href="/wiki/White_House" title="White House">White House</a> to create and improve articles on <a href="/wiki/African_Americans" title="African Americans">African Americans</a> in science, technology, engineering and mathematics (<a href="/wiki/STEM" class="mw-redirect" title="STEM">STEM</a>).<sup id="cite_ref-Wired_5-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Wired-5">[5]</a></sup> The <a href="/wiki/Schomburg_Center" class="mw-redirect" title="Schomburg Center">Schomburg Center</a>, <a href="/wiki/Howard_University" title="Howard University">Howard University</a>, and <a href="/wiki/National_Public_Radio" class="mw-redirect" title="National Public Radio">National Public Radio</a>, also coordinated edit-a-thons to improve coverage of black history.<sup id="cite_ref-NYtimes_2-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NYtimes-2">[2]</a></sup> \xe2\x80\x9cWikipedia editors\xe2\x80\xa6 have held \xe2\x80\x9cedit-a-thons," to "....encourage others to come learn how to\xe2\x80\xa6contribute content on subjects that have been largely ignored.\xe2\x80\x9d<sup id="cite_ref-huffpo-15apr2015_6-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-huffpo-15apr2015-6">[6]</a></sup> Liriano has endorsed Wikipedia edit-a-thons, stating that for Wikipedia\xe2\x80\x99s content to \xe2\x80\x9c\xe2\x80\xa6be representative, everyone has to participate\xe2\x80\x9d</p>\n<p>In 2015 and 2016, the Schomburg Center held a \xe2\x80\x9cBlack Life Matters\xe2\x80\x9d edit-a-thon to coincide with <a href="/wiki/Black_History_Month" title="Black History Month">Black History Month</a>. Volunteer editors added coverage about Black historical individuals and about key concepts in black culture (e.g., about the <a href="/wiki/Harlem_Book_Fair" title="Harlem Book Fair">Harlem Book Fair</a> and about Black costume designer <a href="/wiki/Judy_Dearing" title="Judy Dearing">Judy Dearing</a>)<sup id="cite_ref-huffpo-15apr2015_6-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-huffpo-15apr2015-6">[6]</a></sup> New articles about Black history and Black historical individuals were also created. The 2016 edit-a-thon was organized by <a href="/wiki/AfroCrowd" title="AfroCrowd">AfroCROWD</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-nytimes-29feb2016_8-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nytimes-29feb2016-8">[8]</a></sup></p>\n<p>Wikipedia editors Michael Mandiberg and Dorothy Howard have organized diversity-themed edit-a-thons to \xe2\x80\x9c\xe2\x80\xa6help raise awareness of some of the glaring holes on Wikipedia, and the need for people with diverse backgrounds and knowledge to fill them\xe2\x80\x9d.<sup id="cite_ref-Wired_5-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Wired-5">[5]</a></sup> Liriano stated \xe2\x80\x9cIt\'s really important that people of color know that there\'s this gap\xe2\x80\x9d of coverage of Black history on Wikipedia \xe2\x80\x9c\xe2\x80\xa6and they can correct it\xe2\x80\x9d by participating as editors.<sup id="cite_ref-huffpo-15apr2015_6-9" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-huffpo-15apr2015-6">[6]</a></sup> In the US, the <a href="/wiki/National_Science_Foundation" title="National Science Foundation">National Science Foundation</a> has provided $200,000 to fund research on the issue of bias in the coverage of topics in Wikipedia.<sup id="cite_ref-huffpo-15apr2015_6-10" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-huffpo-15apr2015-6">[6]</a></sup> The National Science Foundation has commissioned two studies of why there is bias in Wikipedia editing.<sup id="cite_ref-Wired_5-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Wired-5">[5]</a></sup></p>\n<p>The <a href="/wiki/Wikimedia_Foundation" title="Wikimedia Foundation">Wikimedia Foundation</a> is trying to deal with the issue of racial bias in Wikipedia. In 2015, it was reported that the Wikipedia Foundation made numerous grants \xe2\x80\x9c\xe2\x80\xa6to organizations in the "Global South" -- including Africa, Latin America, Asia and the Middle East -- with plans to improve [coverage of Global South topics in] Wikipedia.\xe2\x80\x9c<sup id="cite_ref-huffpo-15apr2015_6-11" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-huffpo-15apr2015-6">[6]</a></sup> While Wikipedia supports these edit-a-thons, the organization has always stressed that adequate citations must always be present and neutrality must always be maintained.<sup id="cite_ref-9" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-9">[9]</a></sup> Wikipedia co-founder <a href="/wiki/Jimmy_Wales" title="Jimmy Wales">Jimmy Wales</a> has stated that the Wikimedia Foundation has \xe2\x80\x9ccompletely failed\xe2\x80\x9d to meet its goals of resolving the lack of diversity amongst Wikipedia editors.<sup id="cite_ref-Wired_5-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Wired-5">[5]</a></sup></p>\n<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="See_also">See also</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Racial_bias_on_Wikipedia&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: See also">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>\n<div role="navigation" aria-label="Portals" class="noprint portal plainlist tright" style="margin:0.5em 0 0.5em 1em;border:solid #aaa 1px">\n<ul style="display:table;box-sizing:border-box;padding:0.1em;max-width:175px;background:#f9f9f9;font-size:85%;line-height:110%;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold">\n<li style="display:table-row"><span style="display:table-cell;padding:0.2em;vertical-align:middle;text-align:center"><a href="/wiki/File:AmericaAfrica.svg" class="image"><img alt="icon" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/ca/AmericaAfrica.svg/32px-AmericaAfrica.svg.png" width="32" height="20" class="noviewer" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/ca/AmericaAfrica.svg/48px-AmericaAfrica.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/ca/AmericaAfrica.svg/64px-AmericaAfrica.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="927" data-file-height="592" /></a></span><span style="display:table-cell;padding:0.2em 0.2em 0.2em 0.3em;vertical-align:middle"><a href="/wiki/Portal:African_American" title="Portal:African American">African American portal</a></span></li>\n<li style="display:table-row"><span style="display:table-cell;padding:0.2em;vertical-align:middle;text-align:center"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/ff/Disclogo1.svg/18px-Disclogo1.svg.png" width="18" height="28" class="noviewer" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/ff/Disclogo1.svg/28px-Disclogo1.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/ff/Disclogo1.svg/37px-Disclogo1.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="169" data-file-height="254" /></span><span style="display:table-cell;padding:0.2em 0.2em 0.2em 0.3em;vertical-align:middle"><a href="/wiki/Portal:Discrimination" title="Portal:Discrimination">Discrimination portal</a></span></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<ul>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Criticism_of_Wikipedia" title="Criticism of Wikipedia">Criticism of Wikipedia</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Gender_bias_on_Wikipedia" title="Gender bias on Wikipedia">Gender bias on Wikipedia</a></li>\n</ul>\n<div style="clear:both;"></div>\n<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="References">References</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Racial_bias_on_Wikipedia&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: References">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class="reflist columns references-column-width" style="-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em; list-style-type: decimal;">\n<ol class="references">\n<li id="cite_note-philly-1"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-philly_1-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation web">Melamed, Samantha. <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://articles.philly.com/2015-03-26/entertainment/60480419_1_new-artists-american-art-philadelphia-museum">"Edit-athon aims to put left-out black artists into Wikipedia"</a>. <i>Philly.com</i><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">13 April</span> 2015</span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARacial+bias+on+Wikipedia&amp;rft.atitle=Edit-athon+aims+to+put+left-out+black+artists+into+Wikipedia&amp;rft.aufirst=Samantha&amp;rft.aulast=Melamed&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Philly.com&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Farticles.philly.com%2F2015-03-26%2Fentertainment%2F60480419_1_new-artists-american-art-philadelphia-museum&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-NYtimes-2"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-NYtimes_2-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-NYtimes_2-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation web">Smith, Jada. <a rel="nofollow" class="external t